{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bubley_ver02/data/sn82016181/00529040088/1945100901/1313.xml":{"full_text":"Unemployment Will Ease\nby Spring, WPB Swansong\nBv CHARLES B. DEGGES United Press Staff Correspondent\nProduction Chief Krug predicted today that unemployment will decline by spring and that re\nconversion will be completed by the end of 1916\u2014unless strikes or other disturbing factors\ninterfere.\nKrug\u2019s final report also forecast that the decline in industrial production and national income\nwill be halted early in 1946 with the gross national output levelling off at a rate of around $155,-\n000,000,000 a year. WPB said the war peak was $207,000,000,000 a year and the 1939 rate was\n$88,500,000,000 a year.\nThe reconversion release of some 17.-\n000,000 workers and potential workers\nfrom the armed services and munition\nplants, he added, will involve \u201cfar\nreaching adjustments\" that \u201cwill in\nevitably hurt.\u201d\nWe must, therefore, expect a period\nof hesitation, confusion, and uncertain\nty,\" Krug said. \u201cBut the basic eco\nnomic factors are favorable, if not to\nan immediate full recovery, at least to\nestablishing early in 1946 a floor on\nproduction and employment thru the\nremainder of the reconversion period.\"\nDIFFICULTIES IN 1946\n\"I do not doubt that the country will\nstill be facing difficult economic de\ncisions in late 1946. and beyond,\u201d he\nsaid, \"but the problems will no longer\nbe war production or reconversion\nproblems.\u201d\nThe WPB chief declined to estimate\nwhat the peak of unemployment would\nbe. But, he said, if \u201cadequate allow\nance\" is made for withdrawals from the\nlabor force of servicemen\u2019s wives, other\nwomen who sought temporary war\nwork, and youngsters who return to\nschool, the prospect \u201cdoes not justify\nthe more pessimistic of the forecasts\nwhich have been widely publicized.\u201d\nLabor force withdrawals might total\n4.000,000. he said.\nThe United States smothered her\nAxls enemies with $186,000,000,000 worth\nof weapons, equipment and supplies,\nnot counting the atomic bomb, Krug\nsaid in a war review.\nKrug said that while America's\nj I\n\n11 Ta R W W w W.\u2122\nW%\nNOW is the time to order\nPersonalized XMAS Cards\nWe imprint 50 cards with your\nname for as little as $3.50\nAs much as $25.00\n8 Sample Catalogues!\nHundreds of New Designs!\nGARRISON\nToy and Novelty to., Inc.\n1215 E St. N.W. NA. 1586\nspending for war materials was enor\nmous, it represented only two-fifths of\nthe industrial output. The balance, he\nI said, provided civilians \u201cmore com-\nI modifies and services\u201d than in \u201csuch\ngood pre-war years\u201d as 1937 and 1939.\nKrug revealed not only the total\ni spent on war materiel between July 1.\n1940, and July 31, 1945. but how it\nwas spent:\nAircraft. $44,442,000,000.\nNaval and merchant ships, $40,694\n000.000\nGuns and fire control, $10,801,000,000.\nAmmunition. $19,734,000,000.\nCombat and motor vehicles, $21,529.-\n000.000.\nCommunication and electronic equip\nment, $10,659,000,000.\nOther equipment and supplies, S3B.-\n148.000.000\nPANTS! SLACKS!\n11l BOYS\u2019 LONGIES!\nI It' F.r School or Dress 55.H5 \u2022i*\u2019\nK 11 I No Chsrge tor Adjusting Lrnstbs!\nI 1 I J WASHINGTON PANTS CO.\nHl \"Wear\u2014MS\u2014Slacks\u201d\n741 Sth St. N.W. Open Thors, \u2019til\nFanny Farmer\u2019s\n\u201cBOSTON COOK BOOK\u201d\nOnly $1.98\nBARGAIN BOOK SHOP\n9th St. N. W.\n*W\u00ab Fay Coed Fricet for Goed Books\"\nOpen Evening* \u2019Til 9 Call DI- 5007\nLois Andrews to Wed\nHOLLYWOOD, Oct. 9 Lois An\ndrews. 20, the beautiful showgirl who\nmarried graying comedian George Jes\nsel at 16 and divorced him two years\nlater, said today she will be married\nearly next month to radio crooner Da\nvid Street.\nG. I. HOME LOANS\nHow Uncle Sam Helps\nVeterans Buy a Home\nunder the \"G. I. g\nBill of Hights j\nYOU, as an honorably discharged veteran o! World War 11,\nare entitled to buy or build your own home on 